'''''The Song of One Harp''''' was a [[book]] written by [[Storm Silverhand]] in the {{YearlinkName|1302}}.{{Cite polyhedron/57/The Everwinking Eye: At Home in Maskyr's Eye|20}}{{Cite web/The Candlekeep Collection}}
{{quote|
Where lies the heart of a realm? Its throne, some say. The one who sits upon it, others affirm, trying to appear more wise. Nay, still others say, it is the one who stands, whispering, behind it.

None of these, I tell you. No temple or castle, no sacred grove or mountain height holds the heart of a land of [[Faer√ªn]]. If you seek such a thing, you will find it in the eyes and toil-scarred hands of the farmers and yeomen who work the land, who answer the commands of priest and king, who help those in need, and who raise club, spade, or handy rock to defend their own.

Go then, and find hearts. When you have done that, you can begin the truly difficult task: finding truths in any heart you have found.

Search well; a lifetime is scarce time enough to find a handful of truth.|Storm Silverhand, ''The Song of One Harp''}}
